Your engineering strengths cluster in three areas:

**Systems and architectures you build:** You've consistently delivered across the full stack — from foundational libraries (Friday V2, finance-tracker) to backend services (FastAPI REST API in Friday), frontend applications (React SPA in MindWell, Next.js in vivaha), and tooling (CLI in Friday V3). This breadth suggests comfort moving between layers and translating requirements into appropriate architectural choices.

**Repeated patterns across projects:** You've identified library abstraction as a solved pattern, having applied it in both Friday V2 and finance-tracker. This signals you recognize when to extract common logic and can execute that discipline consistently.

**Language breadth:** You work across 9 languages spanning systems (Rust), scripting (Shell, Python), frontend (TypeScript, JavaScript, CSS, HTML), data (SQL), and documentation (Markdown). This range suggests adaptability and the ability to pick tools that fit the problem rather than defaulting to one stack.

**Complex system handling:** Your most mature work—Friday V3 (92 files, 4 packages) and MindWell (238 files)—shows you can scale beyond toy projects. More importantly, you've avoided circular dependencies in nearly all systems, including high-complexity ones. The exception (Friday's core/pipeline.py <-> core/executor.py) is notable precisely because it's rare in your portfolio, suggesting you treat coupling as something to catch and resolve.

**Confidence: Medium.** These patterns are grounded in architecture labels, file counts, and language detection, not in commit velocity or project outcomes. I haven't traced *why* these choices worked or what the systems do.
